---
title: Ancho BBQ Burgers with Griddled Onion & Roasted Asparagus
description: Ready to amp up burger night? Meet ancho—the slightly spicier chili powder of your BBQ dreams. Here you’ll mix it with tangy red pepper jam and BBQ sauce for a savory slather on toasted buns. Sandwiched between all that flavor are juicy beef patties and tender smoky onion rounds. And since none of these flavors can go to waste, you’ll mix the remaining ancho BBQ sauce with mayo for a creamy potato wedge dipper. This definitely ancho average burger!
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/638528d914f5bd206606ed14-e1208354.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/64651b1258909a3325c8bc33.pdf
author: HelloFresh
time required: 35 minutes
nutrition:
  calories: 860 kcal
  fat: 53 g
  saturated fat: 16 g
  carbohydrates: 72 g
  sugar: 30 g
  protein: 30 g
  fiber: 3 g
  sodium: 870 mg
cuisine: North America
course: main course
servings: 2
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/ancho-bbq-burgers-64651b1258909a3325c8bc33
---

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Slice @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch-thick wedges. Toss on a #baking sheet{} with a
drizzle of @cooking oil{}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until lightly
browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Trim and discard woody bottom ends from @asparagus{6%ounce}. Swap in asparagus for
potatoes; roast for ~{10-12%minutes}.

Meanwhile, peel and slice @red onion{1} into ¼-inch-thick rounds, keeping layers
intact. Halve @potato buns{2}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @red pepper jam{1}, @ancho chili powder{1%teaspoon},
@BBQ sauce{4%tablespoon}, and @water{2%tsp}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add onion
rounds and cook until tender and browned at the edges, ~{3-5%minutes} per side.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Transfer to a #plate{}.

Meanwhile, in a #large bowl{}, combine @ground beef{10%ounce}, @salt{}, and
@pepper{}. Form into two patties, each slightly wider than a burger bun.

Once onion rounds are done, heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in same pan over
medium-high heat. Add patties and cook to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per
side.

While patties cook, toast buns until golden brown. Evenly spread cut sides with
half the ancho BBQ sauce (you'll use the rest in the next step).

Add @mayonnaise{2%tablespoon} to bowl with remaining ancho BBQ sauce; stir to
combine.

Fill buns with patties and griddled onion. Divide burgers and potato wedges
between plates. Serve BBQ mayo on the side for dipping.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.